solar radiation is a function of astronomy, regional geography (latitude), aspect, time of day and year

ponds are a function of topographic position, stream flow and beaver dam construction

outwash plains are a function of geology

mudflats are a function of elevation and slope and flooding disturbance

marine bottom topographic position is a function of elevation, slope
marine current is a function of oceanography, topographic position, tidal cycle
marine current direction is a function of oceanography, tidal cycle

marine substrate is a function of geology, water sediment load and marine topographic position
water depth is a function of water table and stream flow

water oxygenation is a function of stream gradient

groundwater recharge is the result of precipitation (climate) infiltrated through the soil (soil drainage)
groundwater discharge is a function of the water table and elevation
groundwater table is a function of topographic position, geology, soil depth, and precipitation
stream flow is a function of precipitation, groundwater discharge, and stream

stream gradient is a function of stream, slope

stream origin is a function of stream source
stream substrate is a function of stream, soil type, surface rock coverage, and alluvial deposition
rock type is a function of geology
rock size is a function of geology
rock coverage is a function of geology, topographic position (and stochasticity)

bedrock type is a function of geology

surficial geology is a function of geology
talus slope is a function of numerous rocks, from cobbles to boulders, lodged on a slope
soil type is a function of time, climate, vegetation type, surficial and bedrock geology, and slope

soil depth is a function of soil type and topographic position

mapping note:  0 = marine waters; 1 = shallow soils; 2 = moderately deep; 3 = deep soils

soil salinity is a function of soil type, tidal level and salt spray
soil drainage is a function of soil type and slope
soil moisture is a function of evapotranspiration, precipitation, topographic position and soil drainage
soil fertility is a function of soil type
soil organic material is a function of vegetation type, soil type, and time since disturbances that reduce soil organic matter (e.g. fire, animal disturbance)
erosion is a function of vegetation cover, slope, precipitation
aeolian deposition is a function of topographic exposure, aerial sediment load, and time
alluival deposition is a function of water sediment load, water flow, and time
rocky shores is a function of surface rock coverage, rock size (larger than gravel) and shoreline
gravelly shores is a function of surface rock coverage, rock size (gravel size) and shoreline

near-shore is a function of distance from shoreline toward the ocean
inland is a function of distance from shoreline
navigable waters is a function of water depth and current
fuel loading is a function of vegetation type and time since last fire

salt spray is a function of distance from shoreline, (marine) wave energy and exposure to prevailing winds

a community of the intertidal gravelly or rocky shores of brackish tidal rivers and creeks where water salinity ranges from .5 to 18.0 ppt.  Usually sparsely vegetated.

a shrubland community that forms the ecotone between salt marsh and upland vegetation.  Salinity levels are generally lower here than in the salt marsh (soil pore salinity ranges 7 ppt to 27 ppt); and the elevation is higher.

the aquatic community of the permanently flooded portion of a coastal plain pond with seasonally, and annually fluctuating water levels.  These are shallow, groundwater-fed ponds that occur in kettle-holes or shallow depressions.

the gently sloping shore of a coastal plain pond with seasonally and annually fluctuating water levels.  Substrate is sandy, gravelly or mucky.  Vegetative cover varies with the water levels.

a hardwood forest that occurs on mineral soils on low terraces of river floodplains and river deltas.  Sites are characterized by their flood regime: low areas are flooded annually in the spring, and high areas are flooded irregularly.
a hardwood swamp that occurs in poorly drained depressions, usually on inorganic soils.  This is a broadly defined community with many regional and edaphic variants.

a conifer or mixed swamp that occurs on organic soils along streams and in poorly drained depressions of the coastal plain.
a community with extremely sparse vegetation that occurs on unstable sand, gravel, or cobble ocean shores above mean high tide, where the shore is modified by storm waves and wind erosion.

a community that occurs along the shores of lakes and streams on outcrops of calcareous rocks such as limestone and dolomite.  Vegetation is sparse; most plants are rooted in rock crevices.  Mosses and lichens may be common on the rocks.

a community that occurs on vertical exposures of resistant, non-calcareous bedrock (such as quartzite, sandstone or schist) or consolidated material.  There is minimal soil development, and vegetation is sparse.
a community that occurs on vertical exposures of resistant, calcareous bedrock (such as limestone or dolomite) or consolidated material.  There is minimal soil development, and vegetation is sparse.
